    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the HVAC BTU Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Choosing the right size heating or cooling system is essential for comfort and energy efficiency. Enter the room size in square feet, ceiling height, insulation quality, your climate zone, and the number of windows. The calculator starts with a baseline of 20 BTU per square foot and adjusts for each factor. Higher ceilings increase the volume of air to condition, poor insulation allows more heat transfer, and each window adds approximately 1,000 BTU of heat gain or loss.
      </p>
      <p>
        The recommended BTU value is rounded up to the nearest 1,000, and the equivalent tonnage is provided for central HVAC sizing. One ton of cooling capacity equals 12,000 BTU per hour. An oversized system will short-cycle, wasting energy and failing to dehumidify properly. An undersized system will run continuously and struggle to maintain comfortable temperatures during extreme weather.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Factors That Affect BTU Requirements</h2>
      <p>
        Room square footage is the primary driver of BTU requirements, but several other factors significantly affect the total. Ceiling height matters because air conditioning and heating systems must condition the entire volume of air, not just the floor area. A room with 10-foot ceilings contains 25 percent more air than the same room with 8-foot ceilings and requires proportionally more capacity.
      </p>

      <h3>Insulation and Building Envelope</h3>
      <p>
        Insulation quality determines how quickly heat transfers through walls, ceilings, and floors. Poorly insulated homes built before the 1980s may have R-values well below current code requirements and can need 20 to 30 percent more capacity. Homes with modern insulation, double-pane windows, and sealed air barriers retain conditioned air much more effectively. Upgrading insulation is often more cost-effective than installing a larger HVAC system.
      </p>

      <h3>Climate Zone and Sun Exposure</h3>
      <p>
        Climate zone affects the peak heating or cooling demand. Hot southern climates with summer temperatures above 95 degrees Fahrenheit require more cooling capacity, while cold northern climates with winter temperatures below zero need more heating capacity. Sun exposure is another factor. South-facing and west-facing rooms with large windows receive more solar heat gain, which increases cooling demand in summer. Shade trees and window treatments can significantly reduce solar gain.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do I calculate BTU for a room?</h3>
      <p>
        Multiply the room square footage by 20 BTU per square foot as a baseline. Adjust for ceiling height, insulation quality, climate zone, and the number of windows. The result is rounded up to the nearest 1,000 BTU.
      </p>

      <h3>How many BTU per square foot do I need?</h3>
      <p>
        The general rule is 20 BTU per square foot for standard 8-foot ceilings with average insulation in a moderate climate. Hot climates may need 22 to 24 BTU per square foot, while cold climates may need 30 to 35 BTU per square foot for heating.
      </p>

      <h3>What size air conditioner do I need for my room?</h3>
      <p>
        A 150 square foot room needs about 5,000 BTU. A 300 square foot room needs about 7,000 BTU. A 500 square foot room needs 10,000 to 12,000 BTU. A 1,000 square foot area needs 18,000 to 21,000 BTU.
      </p>

      <h3>What factors increase BTU requirements?</h3>
      <p>
        Many windows, poor insulation, high ceilings, hot climates, rooms above garages, kitchens, and rooms with many occupants all increase BTU requirements. Each factor can add 10 to 30 percent to the base calculation.
      </p>

      <h3>What is a ton in HVAC terms?</h3>
      <p>
        One ton equals 12,000 BTU per hour. Residential systems typically range from 1.5 to 5 tons. A 3-ton unit provides 36,000 BTU per hour and can cool approximately 1,500 to 1,800 square feet in a moderate climate.
      </p>

